╔═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗
║  SHIP'S ARCHIVE: Processes                                    ║
║  Classification: Concept                                      ║
╚═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝

┌─ ORIGIN STORY ─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                                                                │
│  Unix process management evolved at Bell Labs in the early    │
│  1970s. The fork() system call (create a copy of a process)   │
│  and exec() (replace the current program) appeared around     │
│  1971. This fork-exec model was revolutionary - lightweight,  │
│  hierarchical, and elegant. Every Unix process is a child     │
│  of another, forming a tree rooted at process 1 (init).       │
│  Tools like ps and kill emerged by mid-1970s.                 │
│                                                                │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

┌─ MENTAL MODEL ─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                                                                │
│  Every running program is a PROCESS with a unique ID (PID):   │
│                                                                │
│        Process Tree:                                           │
│        ┌────────────┐                                          │
│        │  init (1)  │  ← The ancestor of all processes        │
│        └─────┬──────┘                                          │
│              │                                                 │
│        ┌─────┴─────┐                                           │
│        ▼           ▼                                           │
│    ┌────────┐  ┌────────┐                                      │
│    │ bash   │  │ sshd   │                                      │
│    │ (1234) │  │ (456)  │                                      │
│    └────┬───┘  └────────┘                                      │
│         │                                                      │
│    ┌────┴────┐                                                 │
│    ▼         ▼                                                 │
│ ┌──────┐ ┌──────┐                                              │
│ │ vim  │ │ grep │                                              │
│ │(5678)│ │(5679)│                                              │
│ └──────┘ └──────┘                                              │
│                                                                │
│  Key commands:                                                 │
│                                                                │
│    ps          → list your processes                          │
│    ps aux      → list ALL processes (a=all users, u=detail)   │
│    top / htop  → live process monitor                         │
│    kill PID    → send termination signal                      │
│    kill -9 PID → force kill (SIGKILL, cannot be ignored)      │
│                                                                │
│  Background jobs:                                              │
│    command &   → run in background                            │
│    jobs        → list background jobs                         │
│    fg          → bring job to foreground                      │
│    Ctrl+Z      → suspend current process                      │
│    bg          → resume suspended process in background       │
│                                                                │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

┌─ CONNECTIONS ──────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                                                                │
│  • Works well with: grep (ps aux | grep name), pipes          │
│  • Related: nohup (survive logout), screen/tmux (sessions)    │
│  • Builds toward: System administration, debugging, DevOps    │
│                                                                │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

┌─ ARIA'S INSIGHT ───────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                                                                │
│  "When something's stuck, 'ps aux | grep processname' finds   │
│  its PID. Then 'kill PID' asks it to stop gracefully. If      │
│  that fails, 'kill -9 PID' forces it - but use sparingly,     │
│  as it doesn't let the process clean up. And remember:        │
│  'kill' doesn't mean 'destroy' - it means 'send a signal'.    │
│  The default signal is SIGTERM (please stop)."                │
│                                                                │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
